definition.value: The conjugate base of a nucleoside 5'-phosphate.
Zwitterionic form of 6-aminopenicillanic acid arising from migration of a proton from the carboxy group to the 6-amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate acid of codeine arising from protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An  ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of tryptamine arising from protonation of the primary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A  morphinane alkaloid that is a hydrogenated ketone derivative of morphine. A semi-synthetic drug, it is a centrally acting pain medication of the opioid class.
A peptide anion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups and protonation of the glutamyl amino group of glutathione; major species at pH 7.3.
Trianion of nucleoside diphosphate arising from deprotonation of all three free OH groups of the diphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of D-methionine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate acid of oleandomycin arising from protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of creatine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the guanidino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of beta-alanine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of L-alanine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A D-alpha-amino acid zwitterion that is D-phenylalanine in which a proton has been transferred from the carboxy group to the amino group. It is the major species at pH 7.3.
An organic anion that is the conjugate base of riboflavin resulting from the removal of a proton from the nitrogen at position 3 (between the two carbonyl groups). Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of D-glutamine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate acid of a primary aliphatic amine.
Trication of streptomycin arising from protonation of the guanidino and secondary amino groups.

An aminoquinoline that is chloroquine in which one of the N-ethyl groups is hydroxylated at position 2. An antimalarial with properties similar to chloroquine that acts against erythrocytic forms of malarial parasites, it is mainly used as the sulfate salt for the treatment of lupus erythematosus, rheumatoid arthritis, and light-sensitive skin eruptions.
An ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of cysteamine; major species at pH 7.3.
The dianion of a nucleoside monophosphate: major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of L-asparagine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A nucleoside 5'-monophosphate(2-) that results from the removal of two protons from the phosphate group of IMP; major species at pH 7.3.
The R- (less active) enantiomer of ketamine.
A nucleoside 5'-diphosphate(3-) arising from deprotonation of the three triphosphate OH groups of cytidine 5'-diphosphate (CDP); major species at pH 7.3.
Conjugate acid of carbon monoxide arising from protonation of the carbon; major species at pH 7.3.
Dianion of glycerol 2-phosphate arising from deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of L-phenylalanine; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate acid of morphine arising from protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Trianion of nucleoside triphosphate arising from deprotonation of three of the four free triphosphate OH groups.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion where the hydroxy group is placed at position 2 (alpha to the carboxy group) and has (S)-stereochemistry; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion of N(5)-ethyl-L-glutamine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The organophosphate oxoanion formed by loss of 2 protons from each of the phosphate groups of 1D-myo-inositol.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of (S)-atropine arising from protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A N-alkylpiperazine that is piperzine in which the nitrogens atoms are substituted by 2-(2-hydroxyethoxy)ethyl and (4-chlorophenyl)(phenyl)methyl groups respectively.
The ionic polymer obtained by global deprotonation of the carboxy groups of alginic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of O-phosphoethanolamine arising from deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups and protonation of the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The trianion arising from deprotonation of the diphosphate hydroxy groups and the imide nitrogen of flavin mononucleotide (FMN). Major species at pH 7.3.
A quadruply-charged organic cation arising from protonation of the four amino groups of kanamycin A; major species at pH 7.3.
A flavonoid oxoanion that is the conjugate base of (S)-naringenin, arising from selective deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
The ammonium betaine formed from 1-acyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion where the hydroxy group is placed at position 2 (alpha to the carboxy group) and has (R)-stereochemistry; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of L-tyrosine; major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of any acyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of L-glutamine; major species at pH 7.3.

A synthetic ergot alkaloid, structurally related to the oxytocic agent methylergonovine and to the potent hallucinogen LSD and used prophylactically to reduce the frequency and intensity of severe vascular headaches.
An ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of histamine protonated on the side-chain nitrogen.
The conjugate base of a phosphatidyl-L-serine compound.
Dianion of deamido-NAD(+) arising from deprotonation of phosphate and carboxylic acid functions.
